ore robust, it might introduce complications like native reflection. I'll need to guide users about disabling the WADL feature to avoid issues with JAXB dependencies in JDK 21.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing setup requirements for tests**\\n\\nI'm dealing with additional setup concerns. The prompt action \\\"advisory_preparation\\\" looks like it's intended for agent guidance, indicating that setup could involve an extra Maven dependency, a Docker image, or an environment property. If generated tests reflect normal usage, disabling WADL could limit coverage, particularly for Jersey's WADL path. But I want to avoid unnecessary dependencies. The context suggests determining if extra setup is needed before meaningful coverage is possible, which I need to clarify further.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying test-code setup guidance**\\n\\nI’m considering how to handle environment variables, system properties, and other necessary test-code setups by placing them in agent guidance. It seems I have two valid approaches, but I'm trying to figure out which is more suitable. The directive specifically asks for details about an \\\"extra Maven dependency\\\" if that's required. I need to look deeper into what library dependencies might be necessary for this setup process to ensure everything functions smoothly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering server setup risks**\\n\\nI could suggest using a local Grizzly HttpServer with a temporary JAX-RS resource and a random loopback port, ensuring to stop the server during cleanup. It's important that when tests intentionally disable WADL, the JAXB dependency might not get used. I need to consider risks, like using outdated Jersey/Grizzly versions and whether local verification is reliable. If WADL endpoints need JAXB, I may need to add `jaxb-runtime` to minimize risks. Let's test this with `org.glassfish.jaxb:jaxb-runtime:2.3.1`.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_TC6p6bKbig627jeDgEpPrCdh|fc_04715431ba2212ec016a41267f4cc4819781d908416ef48e5b", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d); cd \"$tmp\"; cat > pom.xml <<'EOF'\n<project xmlns=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd\">\n<modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion><groupId>x</groupId><artifactId>x</artifactId><version>1</version>\n<dependencies>\n<dependency><groupId>com.sun.jersey</groupId><artifactId>jersey-grizzly2</artifactId><version>1.9</version></dependency>\n<dependency><groupId>org.glassfish.jaxb</groupId><artifactId>jaxb-runtime</artifactId><version>2.3.1</version></dependency>\n</dependencies>\n</project>\nEOF\nmvn -q dependency:build-classpath -Dmdep.outputFile=cp.txt\ncat > TestJerseyGrizzly.java <<'EOF'\nimport com.sun.jersey.api.container.grizzly2.GrizzlyServerFactory; import com.sun.jersey.api.core.*; import javax.ws.rs.*; import javax.ws.rs.core.UriBuilder; import java.net.*; import org.glassfish.grizzly.http.server.HttpServer;\npublic class TestJerseyGrizzly { @Path(\"/hello\") public static class HelloResource { @GET public String hello(){return \"hello\";} } public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception { ResourceConfig config = new DefaultResourceConfig(HelloResource.class); HttpServer server = GrizzlyServerFactory.createHttpServer(UriBuilder.fromUri(\"http://127.0.0.1/\").port(0).build(), config); try { int port=server.getListeners().iterator().next().getPort(); HttpURLConnection conn=(HttpURLConnection)new URL(\"http://127.0.0.1:\"+port+\"/application.wadl\").openConnection(); System.out.println(conn.getResponseCode()); System.out.println(conn.getContentType()); System.out.println(conn.getInputStream().readNBytes(50).length); } finally { server.stop(); } } }\nEOF\njavac -cp \"$(cat cp.txt)\" TestJerseyGrizzly.java && java -cp \".:$(cat cp.txt)\" TestJerseyGrizzly", "timeout": 120}}],